- "shining star" refers to the player who has the highest number of games played and the highest average points scored;
- "played the most" refers to the total number of games played by the player;
- "averaged the highest points" refers to the average points scored by the player.

- "standout player" refers to the player with the highest average points scored in all-star games;
- "average points scored" is calculated by summing the points scored by a player in all-star games and dividing by the number of games played;
- "all-star games" are special games where the best players from different teams compete against each other.

- "average performance" refers to the average points per game for each team;
- "brilliance of their all-star players" refers to the average points scored by all-star players;
- "stand out above the crowd of all teams" means the team's average points are greater than the overall average of all teams' average points.

- "Point guards" are the primary ball handlers and playmakers in basketball;
- "All-star games" are annual exhibitions featuring the top players from each team;
- "Plus-minus rating" indicates the point difference when a player is on the court;
- "Since the dawn of the 1980s" refers to the years after 1980.

- "Shining stars" refers to players with a high number of all-star game appearances;
- "Graced the all-star stage" refers to the number of times a player has been selected for an all-star game;
- "Brilliance of their current team's average performance" refers to the average points per game scored by the team the player is currently playing for.

- "Elite trio" refers to the top 3 teams;
- "Shone the brightest" refers to having the highest average points per game;
- "For each season" means the ranking is done separately for each season.

- "small forwards (SF)" are players who typically play a versatile role on the basketball court, often combining scoring, rebounding, and defense;
- "averaged more than 20 points per game" refers to the player's performance in terms of scoring;
- "won more than one award" indicates that the player has received recognition for their performance in multiple instances.

- "all-star games" refer to special games where the best players from a league are selected to play;
- "average performance" includes average points scored, field goals made, three-pointers made, and free throws made;
- "accolades" refer to awards or honors received by players for their exceptional performance.
